# Kiro Agent Compartmentalization & Smart Routing — Final Report

**Lead Investigator**: Head Agent (9ecac4c7)
**Date**: 2026-04-22
**Investigation Streams**: c1-internet, c2-kb, c3-context, c4-docs, c5-internal

---

## Executive Summary

The kiro-agents MCP server suffers from three compounding problems: (1) every agent has `"tools": ["*"]` which loads all MCP tools into context, consuming thousands of tokens before the agent writes a single word; (2) five agents are functionally identical 53-tool clones with no specialization; and (3) there is no discovery mechanism — callers must know agent names in advance.

The fix is concrete and achievable in three phases. The core insight from five parallel investigation streams is that **the `allowedTools` lists are already being enforced** — `--trust-all-tools` only bypasses confirmation prompts, not tool visibility. The real problem is that the `allowedTools` lists themselves are too broad, and the `tools: ["*"]` field loads every MCP server's full tool catalog into context regardless. Fixing `tools` to list only the needed MCP servers per agent, combined with a ChromaDB-backed `find_agent` tool for smart routing, solves both problems with minimal code.

**Estimated impact**: 60–90% context reduction per agent invocation; agent routing becomes self-service.

---

## Confirmed Findings

### F1 — All 14 agents have `"tools": ["*"]` (Confidence: CERTAIN)

**Sources**: c2-kb (programmatic verification), c3-context (direct file inspection), c5-internal (local grep)

Every agent JSON in `~/.kiro/agents/` has `"tools": ["*"]`. This causes kiro-cli to load the full tool catalog from all 9 MCP servers into the agent's context window on every invocation. At ~250–500 tokens per tool definition (AWS MCP Strategy docs, confirmed by c4-docs), 53 tools = 13,000–26,500 tokens of overhead before the agent does any work.

### F2 — `--trust-all-tools` bypasses confirmation only, NOT tool visibility (Confidence: HIGH)

**Sources**: c3-context (CLI help verification), direct kiro-cli `--help` output

```
-a, --trust-all-tools
    Allows the model to use any tool to run commands without asking for confirmation
```

The `allowedTools` lists in agent JSON configs **are** being enforced. The root cause of tool flooding is not that `allowedTools` is bypassed — it's that `tools: ["*"]` loads all MCP servers' tools into context regardless of `allowedTools`. The `allowedTools` field controls auto-approval; the `tools` field controls what's loaded.

**Implication**: Do NOT remove `--trust-all-tools`. It is required for `--no-interactive` mode (agents would hang waiting for confirmation that never comes). Instead, fix the `tools` field.

### F3 — Five agents are identical 53-tool clones (Confidence: CERTAIN)

**Sources**: c2-kb (programmatic count), c3-context (sorted list comparison)

`bug-repro-agent`, `developer-agent`, `developer-prod`, `generic-agent`, and `kiro-agent` all have identical `allowedTools` arrays with 53 entries spanning 5 MCP servers: `@aws-docs`, `@builder-mcp`, `@chrome-tabs`, `@kiro-agents`, `@kiro-checkpoint`. These agents have different prompts but identical tool access — a maintenance and context-cost problem.

### F4 — `open_ghostty_tab` exists in core.py but is not wired into agent launches (Confidence: CERTAIN)

**Sources**: c3-context (line 57 confirmed), c5-internal (grep), direct file read

The function exists and uses the correct Ghostty AppleScript API (confirmed working: Ghostty 1.3.1 installed). It is used in `kiro-investigation/server.py` line 233 for dashboard tabs, but `kiro-agents/server.py` never calls it. Adding one line to `launch()` in `core.py` enables real-time monitoring for every agent launch.

### F5 — ChromaDB is available via the knowledge-base MCP venv (Confidence: CERTAIN)

**Sources**: c3-context (directory exists), direct verification

`~/.mcp-kb-chroma/` exists with a 266-document ChromaDB collection. The knowledge-base MCP venv at `/Users/murivirg/work/github/mcp-knowledge-base/server/.venv/` has `chromadb-1.5.5` installed. ChromaDB uses `ONNXMiniLM_L6_V2` (all-MiniLM-L6-v2 via ONNX runtime — no PyTorch required). ChromaDB can be installed in the kiro-agents venv with `pip install chromadb` (dry-run confirmed: installs cleanly).

### F6 — File-based shared bus pattern is proven in kiro-investigation (Confidence: CERTAIN)

**Sources**: c2-kb, c3-context, c5-internal (all confirmed)

`kiro-investigation/server.py` implements `shared_findings.jsonl`, `directives.jsonl`, `user_input.jsonl`, and `control_bus.jsonl`. This pattern works. It does NOT exist in `kiro-agents` — it would need to be added there for inter-agent communication.

### F7 — Duplicate agent definitions across two directories (Confidence: CERTAIN)

**Sources**: c3-context (confirmed), c5-internal (confirmed)

`correspondence-writer`, `report-creator`, and `internal-investigator` exist in both `~/.kiro/mcp-servers/kiro-agents/agents/` (with `expose_as_tool=True`) and `~/.kiro/agents/` (without). The repo's `agents/` dir version wins for `expose_as_tool` registration (first-dir-wins dedup logic in server.py lines 90/103/105). The `~/.kiro/agents/` version is what kiro-cli uses when `--agent` is specified. These can have divergent prompts silently.

### F8 — MeshClaw 3-layer routing is a proven internal reference (Confidence: HIGH)

**Sources**: c5-internal (wiki verified at w.amazon.com/bin/view/Users/abmitra/MeshClaw-Agent-Router/)

MeshClaw implements exactly the routing system requested: Layer 1 = keyword regex (~5μs), Layer 2 = embedding similarity via local ollama `qwen3-embedding:0.6b` (~5ms), Layer 3 = LLM conductor (fallback). Routes to 50+ specialist agents. Score formula: `0.3 × description_similarity + 0.7 × max_example_similarity`. Thresholds: ≥0.85 strong hint, ≥0.65 suggested.

### F9 — AWS prescriptive guidance explicitly validates the proposed approach (Confidence: HIGH)

**Sources**: c4-docs (52/54 claims confirmed against live AWS docs)

AWS MCP Strategy docs (March 2026) confirm: `tools: ["*"]` is an anti-pattern; 20 tools = 5,000–10,000 tokens per invocation; semantic search over tools is the recommended approach for large tool sets; disparate worker agents (each with minimal tools) are preferred over super-agents for systems with low risk tolerance.

### F10 — Builder-MCP Tool Personalization offers 66% token reduction (Confidence: HIGH)

**Sources**: c5-internal (BuilderHub docs verified)

Builder-MCP has a built-in personalization feature (currently in preview) that uses progressive disclosure to hide rarely-used tools. Up to 66% token reduction. Supported on Kiro CLI. This is a complementary approach to explicit `tools` scoping.

---

## Contradictions Found

### C1 — Root cause: `--trust-all-tools` vs `tools: ["*"]`

**Contradiction**: c3-context's initial findings claimed `--trust-all-tools` "bypasses all allowedTools restrictions" and was the root cause. The c3-context validator then contradicted this, finding the flag only bypasses confirmation prompts.

**Resolution**: The validator is correct. Direct CLI help output confirms: `"Allows the model to use any tool to run commands without asking for confirmation"`. The root cause is `tools: ["*"]` loading all MCP tools into context, not `--trust-all-tools` bypassing `allowedTools`. The fix is to change `tools: ["*"]` to explicit MCP server lists per agent. Do not remove `--trust-all-tools`.

### C2 — ChromaDB "already in the stack" vs "not in the stack"

**Contradiction**: c2-kb initially said ChromaDB is "already available via knowledge-base MCP." The c2-kb validator then contradicted this, saying ChromaDB is not in the kiro-agents venv.
